portant;\"> Yes </td>\n   <td style=\"text-align:center;background-color: rgba(240, 244, 248, 255) !important;\"> Yes </td>\n  </tr>\n</tbody>\n<tfoot><tr><td style=\"padding: 0; \" colspan=\"100%\">\n<span style=\"font-style: italic;\">Notes:</span> <sup></sup> Dependent variable: indicator = 1 if individual/household member returned in year t (conditional on having previously migrated). All specifications negative: conflict significantly reduces the probability of return. Standard errors clustered at village level in brackets. *** p&lt;0.01, ** p&lt;0.05, * p&lt;0.10.</td></tr></tfoot>\n</table>\n\n`````\n:::\n:::\n\n\n::: {.callout-important}\n**Key finding — Permanence of displacement:** Conflict intensity (column 2) reduces the probability of individual return by **34 percentage points per unit** of the casualty rate. At the household level (column 4), the effect is −29 pp. Since the dep. var. mean is ~8–14%, these are large effects that imply civil war–induced household dissolution is largely **permanent**.\n\nThis has important implications for policy: interventions targeting conflict-affected households must account for the fact that migration-induced compositional changes are unlikely to self-reverse even after peace is restored.\n:::\n\n---\n\n## Summary: Effect Sizes\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n![Summary of Main Coefficients — Effect on Migration Probabilities](results_files/figure-html/fig-summary-effects-1.png){#fig-summary-effects width=1400}\n:::\n:::\n\n\n---\n\n## References {.unnumbered}\n\n::: {#refs}\n:::\n",
